{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01MTycJWd5Ws8pV1nSoGZtKT","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All three jobs completed successfully. Here's the full summary:\n\n---\n\n## Results Summary\n\n### Step 1: Configuration Diagnosis\nThe deployment started cleanly — the Spark master registered a worker successfully and the baseline job launched without errors. The `skew-job.yaml` runs in `--master local[2]` mode (self-contained in the container), so it doesn't depend on the external Spark cluster for correctness. No blocking bugs were present; the deployment was functional as-is.\n\n### Step 2–4: All Three Jobs Completed\n\n| Strategy | Elapsed | Optimization | Benefit |\n|----------|---------|-------------|---------|\n| **baseline** | **30.6s** | none | skewed shuffle join (stragglers) |\n| **broadcast** | **15.4s** | broadcast_join | no shuffle, no skew |\n| **aqe** | **17.7s** | aqe_skew_join | auto-splits hot partitions |\n\nAll three jobs status: `Complete 1/1`.\n\n### Step 5: Performance Comparison\n\n**Broadcast join** is the winner at **2.0x speedup** (30.6s → 15.4s). It avoids the shuffle entirely by broadcasting the small `products` table to every executor — hot product IDs 1–5 no longer cause partition straggling.\n\n**AQE** is also effective at **1.7x speedup** (30.6s → 17.7s). It keeps the shuffle join but auto-detects and splits skewed partitions at runtime. More overhead than broadcast, but works even when the small table isn't small enough to broadcast.\n\n**Key insight:** For this workload (small `products` table, ~100 rows), broadcast join is optimal. AQE is the safer default when the \"small\" side is unknown or too large to broadcast reliably."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":149,"cache_read_input_tokens":43549,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":149},"output_